  "question": "Carla is downloading a 200 GB file. Normally she can download 2 GB/minute, but 40% of the way through the download, Windows forces a restart to install updates, which takes 20 minutes. Then Carla has to restart the download from the beginning. How load does it take to download the file?",
  "prompt": "Carla is downloading a 200 GB file. Normally she can download 2 GB/minute, but 40% of the way through the download, Windows forces a restart to install updates, which takes 20 minutes. Then Carla has to restart the download from the beginning. How load does it take to download the file?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "160",
  "generated_text": "To solve this problem, we need to calculate the total time Carla spends downloading the file, accounting for the pause and the restart.\n\n**Step 1: Calculate the progress made before the restart.**\nThe download takes 2 GB per minute for 40 minutes.\n$$ \\text{Progress} = 2 \\text{ GB/min} \\times 40 \\text{ min} = 80 \\text{ GB} $$\n\n**Step 2: Determine the remaining distance.**\nThe total file size is 200 GB. After downloading 80 GB, the remaining amount is:\n$$ \\text{Remaining} = 200 \\text{ GB} - 80 \\text{ GB} = 120 \\text{ GB} $$\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the time to download the remaining amount.**\nSince the download speed remains 2 GB/minute:\n$$ \\text{Time to finish} = \\frac{120 \\text{ GB}}{2 \\text{ GB/min}} = 60 \\text{ minutes} $$\n\n**Step 4: Calculate the total time including the restart.**\nThe restart itself takes 20 minutes.\n$$ \\text{Total Time} = \\text{Time to restart} + \\text{Time to download remaining} $$\n$$ \\text{Total Time} = 20 \\text{ min} + 60 \\text{ min} = 80 \\text{ minutes} $$\n\nAlternatively, you can think of it as:\n$$ \\text{Total Time} = (40 \\text{ min} \\times 2 \\text{ GB/min}) + 20 \\text{ min} + \\left(\\frac{200 - 80}{2} \\text{ GB}\\right)",
